 a unified revolution rather than a civil war.Williams argues that the Second Amendment has been based on myths about America-the Framers’ belief in American unity and modern interpreters’ belief in American distrust and disunity. Neither of these myths, however, will adequately curb political violence. Williams suggests that the amendment should serve not as a rule of law but as a cultural ideal that promotes our unity on the use of political violence and celebrates our diversity in other areas of life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFirearmsxLaw and legislationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aGovernment, Resistance tozUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPolitical violencezUnited StatesxHistory. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030009562340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030012755340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300127553423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300127553/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY